WEBVTT
Kind: captions
Language: en

00:00:03.894 --> 00:00:05.310
GAIL SIMMONS:
Thanks for having us

00:00:05.310 --> 00:00:06.976
and thanks for giving
me the opportunity

00:00:06.976 --> 00:00:09.280
to spend more time
with Leanne Brown.

00:00:09.280 --> 00:00:12.670
I'm really excited that
you asked me here today

00:00:12.670 --> 00:00:16.730
to speak with you because
it's a topic that's not only

00:00:16.730 --> 00:00:21.510
incredibly timely and important
at this moment in America

00:00:21.510 --> 00:00:25.120
for a lot of reasons,
b but it is something

00:00:25.120 --> 00:00:27.280
that as a person who
eats for a living,

00:00:27.280 --> 00:00:28.780
I think about every day.

00:00:28.780 --> 00:00:32.860
And I think, as someone
who is lucky enough

00:00:32.860 --> 00:00:36.436
to eat well in this
country, as we all are--

00:00:36.436 --> 00:00:38.310
and I know that I can
say that because I just

00:00:38.310 --> 00:00:39.860
had lunch in your cafeteria.

00:00:39.860 --> 00:00:40.120
LEANNE BROWN: Yeah, we know.

00:00:40.120 --> 00:00:41.620
GAIL SIMMONS: And
I know how you all

00:00:41.620 --> 00:00:45.040
eat, which is an
incredible privilege.

00:00:45.040 --> 00:00:47.270
But sadly it has
become a privilege.

00:00:47.270 --> 00:00:50.300
And I think I wanted
to start there,

00:00:50.300 --> 00:00:53.170
so that we can talk a little
bit about how this book came

00:00:53.170 --> 00:00:56.090
to be because it is one of
the most unique stories,

00:00:56.090 --> 00:00:58.830
certainly in cookbook
publishing, of the last decade.

00:00:58.830 --> 00:01:01.509
I mean it really
was born in a way

00:01:01.509 --> 00:01:03.050
that I think could
have only happened

00:01:03.050 --> 00:01:07.330
at this moment in this
country as it happened.

00:01:07.330 --> 00:01:09.550
So, let's go back
for a little bit.

00:01:09.550 --> 00:01:10.800
LEANNE BROWN: You're so right.

00:01:10.800 --> 00:01:14.880
Sometimes people ask me,
how did you start this?

00:01:14.880 --> 00:01:16.750
Or ask for advice
for publishing.

00:01:16.750 --> 00:01:18.940
I'm always like, I'm
not sure we can really

00:01:18.940 --> 00:01:22.020
recreate the bizarre
experience that I had.

00:01:22.020 --> 00:01:25.150
So for those of you who aren't
familiar with the project,

00:01:25.150 --> 00:01:29.145
it actually started out as my
thesis project for my masters

00:01:29.145 --> 00:01:31.270
at NYU in food studies.

00:01:31.270 --> 00:01:34.510
So it was like this
really nerdy big project.

00:01:34.510 --> 00:01:37.480
And because food studies
is this very new field.

00:01:37.480 --> 00:01:39.057
It's only been I
think 15 years--

00:01:39.057 --> 00:01:40.140
GAIL SIMMONS: I would say.

00:01:40.140 --> 00:01:40.670
LEANNE BROWN: --at NYU.

00:01:40.670 --> 00:01:42.340
And I believe that's
the oldest program.

00:01:42.340 --> 00:01:44.230
GAIL SIMMONS: And it's
a very unique program.

00:01:44.230 --> 00:01:46.020
It doesn't exist in
many places at all.

00:01:46.020 --> 00:01:46.936
LEANNE BROWN: Exactly.

00:01:46.936 --> 00:01:49.630
And so, because it's
so new and unique,

00:01:49.630 --> 00:01:51.490
there is no one
specific way that you

00:01:51.490 --> 00:01:52.470
have to do your thesis.

00:01:52.470 --> 00:01:54.250
It's not like an
anthropology degree,

00:01:54.250 --> 00:01:58.000
where you write this long paper
in this very specific style.

00:01:58.000 --> 00:02:01.460
And for me, what I'd been
drawn to during the course

00:02:01.460 --> 00:02:06.783
of the degree, really
it just became clear

00:02:06.783 --> 00:02:08.449
that this was something
that I could do.

00:02:08.449 --> 00:02:11.660
And something that
I was uniquely

00:02:11.660 --> 00:02:13.510
capable of
contributing, which is

00:02:13.510 --> 00:02:16.600
to create a cookbook for people
who are living on a food stamps

00:02:16.600 --> 00:02:17.514
budget.

00:02:17.514 --> 00:02:19.680
GAIL SIMMONS: So let's just
take a minute background

00:02:19.680 --> 00:02:20.970
on food stamps.

00:02:20.970 --> 00:02:26.260
They are a complicated
issue in US politics.

00:02:26.260 --> 00:02:29.960
A very unique and at
moments, actually exciting

00:02:29.960 --> 00:02:33.560
story, in this country
of how they came to.

00:02:38.730 --> 00:02:42.360
The history of them and their
current status in America

00:02:42.360 --> 00:02:43.390
has changed a lot.

00:02:43.390 --> 00:02:50.570
And food stamps, as people know,
are social welfare for people

00:02:50.570 --> 00:02:55.357
who obviously who cannot
afford to pay for their food.

00:02:55.357 --> 00:02:57.690
LEANNE BROWN: Right, for
people with a certain threshold

00:02:57.690 --> 00:02:58.290
right of income.

00:02:58.290 --> 00:02:59.000
GAIL SIMMONS: Right.

00:02:59.000 --> 00:03:00.833
But it takes a lot of
work to prove that you

00:03:00.833 --> 00:03:02.179
are below that threshold.

00:03:02.179 --> 00:03:04.220
LEANNE BROWN: Yeah, even
just doing the paperwork

00:03:04.220 --> 00:03:06.810
is extraordinary.

00:03:06.810 --> 00:03:11.450
It's incredibly difficult
simply to sign up for them.

00:03:11.450 --> 00:03:14.380
And so, the book is
called, "Good and Cheap,"

00:03:14.380 --> 00:03:15.820
not the food stamps cookbook.

00:03:15.820 --> 00:03:18.155
It's called, "Eat Well
on $4/day" because $4

00:03:18.155 --> 00:03:20.880
a day is the average amount
that you have to work with.

00:03:20.880 --> 00:03:25.890
So even after you managed to
sign up, which is no easy feat,

00:03:25.890 --> 00:03:29.030
then suddenly you have
approximately $4 a day

00:03:29.030 --> 00:03:33.160
to work with, which
is an incredible gift.

00:03:33.160 --> 00:03:35.160
But at the same time
is not like, oh ho,

00:03:35.160 --> 00:03:38.300
no problem then,
everything's going to be OK!

00:03:38.300 --> 00:03:40.240
It's still
extraordinarily difficult.

00:03:40.240 --> 00:03:43.670
GAIL SIMMONS: Especially in
places all over the country

00:03:43.670 --> 00:03:45.930
where access to food--

00:03:45.930 --> 00:03:48.310
LEANNE BROWN: Exactly, which
is such an important topic,

00:03:48.310 --> 00:03:49.685
especially while
I was at school.

00:03:49.685 --> 00:03:53.410
And continues to be a really
important field of study

00:03:53.410 --> 00:03:55.470
that a lot of great
minds are working on.

00:03:55.470 --> 00:03:58.140
And I see a lot of hope there.

00:03:58.140 --> 00:04:02.460
But yeah, there's this focus on
not everyone has even a place

00:04:02.460 --> 00:04:06.240
to go grocery shopping to spend
your $4 in an appropriate way.

00:04:06.240 --> 00:04:09.460
You know there might be the
place several miles away.

00:04:09.460 --> 00:04:11.710
And food security looks
different in different places.

00:04:11.710 --> 00:04:14.950
Like the way that it looks in
New York City's sort of food

00:04:14.950 --> 00:04:17.640
insecurity might be,
urban and security

00:04:17.640 --> 00:04:21.420
means having to walk
a half hour somewhere,

00:04:21.420 --> 00:04:24.610
having to take lousy public
transit with heavy bags.

00:04:24.610 --> 00:04:27.750
In the rural countryside,
it might mean only

00:04:27.750 --> 00:04:32.770
being able to afford gas to
go those five towns over once

00:04:32.770 --> 00:04:34.970
a month or something like that.

00:04:34.970 --> 00:04:37.500
So it looks very different
in different places.

00:04:37.500 --> 00:04:40.180
And I was studying
all these big issues

00:04:40.180 --> 00:04:45.870
and becoming really frustrated
by it and angry about it.

00:04:45.870 --> 00:04:48.050
And we'd have in
grad school you have

00:04:48.050 --> 00:04:50.230
all these amazing
conversations with people.

00:04:50.230 --> 00:04:52.459
And you have these intense
conversations in class.

00:04:52.459 --> 00:04:54.500
And then at the end you
always come to this point

00:04:54.500 --> 00:04:57.980
we're you're like, well,
I don't we're going to do.

00:04:57.980 --> 00:04:58.780
We're screwed.

00:04:58.780 --> 00:05:00.340
That's usually where you end up.

00:05:00.340 --> 00:05:05.380
And I just got so tired of
that experience and sort

00:05:05.380 --> 00:05:07.202
of knowing the struggles
that we had ahead.

00:05:07.202 --> 00:05:08.910
And knowing like how
important they were.

00:05:08.910 --> 00:05:11.190
And I never want to
give up on those sort

00:05:11.190 --> 00:05:12.900
of large scale struggles.

00:05:12.900 --> 00:05:15.300
But I also was like desperate
to just do something

00:05:15.300 --> 00:05:16.802
right now that could be of use.

00:05:16.802 --> 00:05:18.260
And that could be
of immediate use.

00:05:18.260 --> 00:05:21.150
That certainly was a response
to the whole problem,

00:05:21.150 --> 00:05:23.260
but was the one thing that
I was sort of good at,

00:05:23.260 --> 00:05:25.760
which was and is cooking.

00:05:25.760 --> 00:05:29.710
I know and as you know,
Gail, and many people

00:05:29.710 --> 00:05:33.400
who work in food knows
the cost of basic food.

00:05:33.400 --> 00:05:37.560
Basic foods are really,
really inexpensive,

00:05:37.560 --> 00:05:39.110
if you know how to
put them together.

00:05:39.110 --> 00:05:41.314
You know if you have
those abilities.

00:05:41.314 --> 00:05:42.230
It's really just work.

00:05:42.230 --> 00:05:43.440
It's a practice.

00:05:43.440 --> 00:05:47.170
And so that was something
that I really wanted to share.

00:05:47.170 --> 00:05:48.950
And I never in a
million years imagined

00:05:48.950 --> 00:05:50.200
it would end up at this scale.

00:05:50.200 --> 00:05:51.744
I had hoped to be
able to have it

00:05:51.744 --> 00:05:53.910
be of use to a few of the
people that I worked with,

00:05:53.910 --> 00:05:55.630
that I volunteered with.

00:05:55.630 --> 00:05:58.980
It's amazing that it has been
as well received as it has.

00:05:58.980 --> 00:06:02.700
I think it just shows that it's
something that a lot of people

00:06:02.700 --> 00:06:03.450
are excited about.

00:06:03.450 --> 00:06:05.140
GAIL SIMMONS: And
there was a hole.

00:06:05.140 --> 00:06:06.265
It hadn't been done before.

00:06:06.265 --> 00:06:09.360
It seems quite
simple that we all,

00:06:09.360 --> 00:06:12.780
no matter I think at
what income you're at,

00:06:12.780 --> 00:06:14.880
and how much access
to good food you have,

00:06:14.880 --> 00:06:16.379
you need to know
what to do with it.

00:06:16.379 --> 00:06:17.870
And that's a complicated topic.

00:06:17.870 --> 00:06:19.210
That's why cookbooks exist--

00:06:19.210 --> 00:06:20.126
LEANNE BROWN: Exactly.

00:06:20.126 --> 00:06:21.700
GAIL SIMMONS: --in
the first place.

00:06:21.700 --> 00:06:23.075
LEANNE BROWN: Even
the best of us

00:06:23.075 --> 00:06:26.230
sometimes are just like, ugh,
I don't know what to do today.

00:06:26.230 --> 00:06:28.530
GAIL SIMMONS: Or you
look at a pantry of food

00:06:28.530 --> 00:06:30.330
and how do you make
that into a meal.

00:06:30.330 --> 00:06:32.560
Moreover, how do you make
it into a nutritious meal,

00:06:32.560 --> 00:06:34.170
but that's also delicious?

00:06:34.170 --> 00:06:34.270
LEANNE BROWN: Yes.

00:06:34.270 --> 00:06:35.560
GAIL SIMMONS: And I think that
there are, for so many years--

00:06:35.560 --> 00:06:36.680
LEANNE BROWN: Something
you look forward to.

00:06:36.680 --> 00:06:37.320
Right.

00:06:37.320 --> 00:06:39.236
GAIL SIMMONS: --that
those have been opposing.

00:06:39.236 --> 00:06:44.410
And I think that especially
at the food stamp

00:06:44.410 --> 00:06:45.864
level and the
level of people who

00:06:45.864 --> 00:06:47.280
need to get access
the most, there

00:06:47.280 --> 00:06:51.240
has been a bit of a disconnect
in the conversation between how

00:06:51.240 --> 00:06:54.440
do we make sure that we eat
well and feed our families,

00:06:54.440 --> 00:06:58.220
but also eat food that we
want to eat that tastes good

00:06:58.220 --> 00:07:01.380
and that we feel
empowered by eating.

00:07:01.380 --> 00:07:02.350
So you are right--

00:07:02.350 --> 00:07:02.820
LEANNE BROWN: And
that is something

00:07:02.820 --> 00:07:05.590
you look forward to because it's
something that we all deserve.

00:07:05.590 --> 00:07:07.360
I mean we all had
this wonderful lunch.

00:07:07.360 --> 00:07:09.027
And you guys get to
have that every day.

00:07:09.027 --> 00:07:10.568
And that's something
that can get you

00:07:10.568 --> 00:07:11.740
through a difficult day.

00:07:11.740 --> 00:07:14.860
And that should be available
for absolutely everyone.

00:07:14.860 --> 00:07:16.880
Everyone deserves
that type of comfort.

00:07:16.880 --> 00:07:19.247
GAIL SIMMONS: That should
be a right, not a privilege.

00:07:19.247 --> 00:07:20.830
So you're writing
your thesis, and you

00:07:20.830 --> 00:07:25.250
decide I'm going to write a
cookbook with recipes that

00:07:25.250 --> 00:07:27.080
fit in the food stamp budget.

00:07:27.080 --> 00:07:28.010
And then what happens?

00:07:28.010 --> 00:07:32.607
Because it took a turn in a way
that I think is worth sharing.

00:07:32.607 --> 00:07:33.440
LEANNE BROWN: Right.

00:07:33.440 --> 00:07:36.640
So after I graduated,
this was December of 2013,

00:07:36.640 --> 00:07:39.200
I had kind of thought, OK,
great, so I've done this,

00:07:39.200 --> 00:07:41.010
now I need to get
it out to people.

00:07:41.010 --> 00:07:42.540
And I initially
thought this would

00:07:42.540 --> 00:07:44.790
be a great tool in the hands
of some of the nonprofits

00:07:44.790 --> 00:07:46.820
that I'd worked with,
that I had volunteered

00:07:46.820 --> 00:07:48.415
with during my degree.

00:07:48.415 --> 00:07:50.040
I was thinking of a
lot of the families

00:07:50.040 --> 00:07:50.998
that I had spoken with.

00:07:50.998 --> 00:07:53.830
I'd just love to be able
to give this to them.

00:07:53.830 --> 00:07:56.234
And so I started out there.

00:07:56.234 --> 00:07:58.150
I was sort of pitching
it to different profits

00:07:58.150 --> 00:08:00.120
and people were
interested in it.

00:08:00.120 --> 00:08:01.360
But no one was really sure.

00:08:01.360 --> 00:08:02.929
At that point It was just a PDF.

00:08:02.929 --> 00:08:04.970
I was kind of scrolling
through it, showing them.

00:08:04.970 --> 00:08:06.220
Like, oh, this is really nice.

00:08:06.220 --> 00:08:09.150
We're not exactly
sure how we'll use it.

00:08:09.150 --> 00:08:11.590
And, again, my
impatience took over.

00:08:11.590 --> 00:08:15.870
And I just decided
in April of 2014

00:08:15.870 --> 00:08:17.870
that I was just going to
create a little website

00:08:17.870 --> 00:08:21.294
and put the book up there and
kind of see what happened.

00:08:21.294 --> 00:08:22.710
I didn't really
have a great plan.

00:08:22.710 --> 00:08:24.334
I wasn't like, well,
I'm going to start

00:08:24.334 --> 00:08:26.534
pitching this to everyone.

00:08:26.534 --> 00:08:27.950
There was no real
rhyme or reason.

00:08:27.950 --> 00:08:30.286
I was just like, I just
want to put it out there.

00:08:30.286 --> 00:08:31.090
GAIL SIMMONS: Did
you tell anybody?

00:08:31.090 --> 00:08:31.920
LEANNE BROWN: And
we'll figure it out.

00:08:31.920 --> 00:08:32.870
GAIL SIMMONS: Dan knew.

00:08:32.870 --> 00:08:33.370
Dan definitely knew.

00:08:33.370 --> 00:08:34.661
LEANNE BROWN: Yeah, I told Dan.

00:08:34.661 --> 00:08:36.169
I told a few of my friends.

00:08:36.169 --> 00:08:40.000
I really didn't tell that
many people, actually.

00:08:40.000 --> 00:08:41.959
So, which is why I was
really surprised when

00:08:41.959 --> 00:08:44.250
one day at the end of April,
just a few weeks after I'd

00:08:44.250 --> 00:08:46.500
made the website, I came home.

00:08:46.500 --> 00:08:49.760
And I opened up my computer
and I had hundreds of emails

00:08:49.760 --> 00:08:51.010
from my website.

00:08:51.010 --> 00:08:53.840
And at that point, it
was the weirdest thing,

00:08:53.840 --> 00:08:55.750
because like Dan
had seen the website

00:08:55.750 --> 00:08:58.020
and my father had
seen the website.

00:08:58.020 --> 00:09:00.840
He had pretty much every day
called to say like, Leanne,

00:09:00.840 --> 00:09:02.840
you've got some typos on
there, can you please--

00:09:02.840 --> 00:09:04.214
GAIL SIMMONS: Mmm,
thank you dad.

00:09:04.214 --> 00:09:05.870
LEANNE BROWN: Yeah, thanks Dad.

00:09:05.870 --> 00:09:09.020
But nobody else had so I
was like, what is going on?

00:09:09.020 --> 00:09:11.630
And it turned out that someone
had posted it on Reddit.

00:09:11.630 --> 00:09:14.130
And it had become a
very popular thread.

00:09:14.130 --> 00:09:18.340
And I was terrified,
instantly terrified,

00:09:18.340 --> 00:09:20.410
assumed the worse, of course.

00:09:20.410 --> 00:09:22.202
And was thinking like,
oh my goodness, it's

00:09:22.202 --> 00:09:24.368
all these people probably
criticizing and saying I'm

00:09:24.368 --> 00:09:24.910
an idiot.

00:09:24.910 --> 00:09:25.951
GAIL SIMMONS: More typos.

00:09:25.951 --> 00:09:28.700
LEANNE BROWN: Yeah,
it's definitely typos.

00:09:28.700 --> 00:09:30.925
And it turned out that
it was the opposite.

00:09:33.430 --> 00:09:35.220
I remember one of
the first e-mails

00:09:35.220 --> 00:09:37.750
that I got that really struck
me was this young man, named

00:09:37.750 --> 00:09:38.510
Christian.

00:09:38.510 --> 00:09:40.349
He said I am a student.

00:09:40.349 --> 00:09:41.390
I'm going back to school.

00:09:41.390 --> 00:09:42.980
I have to go on food
stamps for the first time

00:09:42.980 --> 00:09:44.622
because I have to
cut my hours back.

00:09:44.622 --> 00:09:47.080
And I was so terrified I was
just going to be eating ramen.

00:09:47.080 --> 00:09:48.830
Because that's what
everyone tells you.

00:09:48.830 --> 00:09:51.870
And he said, oh, it's
such a relief to me.

00:09:51.870 --> 00:09:53.650
I'm really excited about this.

00:09:53.650 --> 00:09:57.939
And there were hundreds more
like that with similar stories

00:09:57.939 --> 00:09:59.230
and a lot of different stories.

00:10:02.030 --> 00:10:04.210
The actual thing that really
touched me was not just

00:10:04.210 --> 00:10:05.640
the people who are saying,
this is helpful to me

00:10:05.640 --> 00:10:08.380
right now, which of course
was tremendously validating,

00:10:08.380 --> 00:10:11.547
but was that people were sharing
stories about experiences

00:10:11.547 --> 00:10:12.630
they've had in their past.

00:10:12.630 --> 00:10:15.140
Like growing up with
hunger, talking about,

00:10:15.140 --> 00:10:17.390
my grandparents
who look at looked

00:10:17.390 --> 00:10:19.651
after us did a great job.

00:10:19.651 --> 00:10:21.650
We ate really well, but
I remember our neighbors

00:10:21.650 --> 00:10:23.080
had a really tough time.

00:10:23.080 --> 00:10:24.830
And I wish they'd had
something like this.

00:10:24.830 --> 00:10:26.330
People were sharing
stuff like this.

00:10:26.330 --> 00:10:27.222
It was so incredible.

00:10:27.222 --> 00:10:29.180
And people were creating
this little community,

00:10:29.180 --> 00:10:31.540
sort of saying like, all right,
well, let's help Leanne out.

00:10:31.540 --> 00:10:33.039
Like, how can we
get this out there?

00:10:33.039 --> 00:10:35.141
And I was like, yeah,
guys, what do you think,

00:10:35.141 --> 00:10:36.390
how can we get this out there?

00:10:36.390 --> 00:10:38.460
I don't know what I'm doing.

00:10:38.460 --> 00:10:40.890
And so that was really exciting.

00:10:40.890 --> 00:10:43.680
And after Reddit, it sort of
spread to a few different parts

00:10:43.680 --> 00:10:44.530
of the internet.

00:10:44.530 --> 00:10:47.860
And I realized that I just
needed to have courage.

00:10:47.860 --> 00:10:49.650
I needed to stop like
being a wimp, kind

00:10:49.650 --> 00:10:51.450
of just telling Dan
and just telling

00:10:51.450 --> 00:10:52.650
my dad about these things.

00:10:52.650 --> 00:10:54.175
I needed to go for it.

00:10:54.175 --> 00:10:55.550
GAIL SIMMONS: What
did that mean?

00:10:55.550 --> 00:10:57.549
LEANNE BROWN: That meant
launching a Kickstarter

00:10:57.549 --> 00:10:58.790
to fund an actual print run.

00:10:58.790 --> 00:11:01.420
Because of course the one
very legitimate criticism

00:11:01.420 --> 00:11:04.852
that people had was like,
it's great that it's online.

00:11:04.852 --> 00:11:06.810
And it's very easy to
give things away for free

00:11:06.810 --> 00:11:07.910
on the internet.

00:11:07.910 --> 00:11:11.040
But it's not that easy to
give things away for free

00:11:11.040 --> 00:11:13.400
when they're physical.

00:11:13.400 --> 00:11:15.960
I knew that we wanted to
make physical cookbooks,

00:11:15.960 --> 00:11:17.920
but I just didn't
really know how.

00:11:17.920 --> 00:11:19.650
And so with all
this encouragement

00:11:19.650 --> 00:11:21.775
from all these wonderful
strangers, I was like, OK,

00:11:21.775 --> 00:11:24.380
maybe we can raise some money.

00:11:24.380 --> 00:11:27.150
So we decided to do a
Kickstarter campaign.

00:11:27.150 --> 00:11:30.830
Stole the Tom's shoes model,
the buy one, give one.

00:11:30.830 --> 00:11:33.550
Because it was very important
that this not sort of just

00:11:33.550 --> 00:11:35.670
be a cookbook, it
was very important

00:11:35.670 --> 00:11:38.970
that it remain totally free
and as accessible as possible

00:11:38.970 --> 00:11:41.720
for people for whom it would
really be a genuine burden

00:11:41.720 --> 00:11:44.727
to pay $20 for a cookbook.

00:11:44.727 --> 00:11:46.810
I just didn't want to put
up that kind of barrier.

00:11:46.810 --> 00:11:49.880
So luckily Kickstarter
exists, you can kind of

00:11:49.880 --> 00:11:52.240
do what you need to do,
just put it out there,

00:11:52.240 --> 00:11:53.550
ask people for this.

00:11:53.550 --> 00:11:54.800
So we launched the campaign.

00:11:54.800 --> 00:11:56.790
We asked for $10,000.

00:11:56.790 --> 00:11:59.240
And we figured with
that-- Dan helped

00:11:59.240 --> 00:12:01.240
with these calculations--
that we could

00:12:01.240 --> 00:12:02.570
print about 1,000 books total.

00:12:02.570 --> 00:12:04.160
500 we'd be able to give away.

00:12:04.160 --> 00:12:05.880
500 we'd give to our backers.

00:12:05.880 --> 00:12:09.410
And we could sort of break even
and get by and it would be OK.

00:12:09.410 --> 00:12:13.440
But we reached that goal in the
first 36 hours of the campaign.

00:12:13.440 --> 00:12:15.520
So it's like a day
and a half later.

00:12:15.520 --> 00:12:16.370
It was unbelievable.

00:12:16.370 --> 00:12:18.036
And I have to say
just because I am here

00:12:18.036 --> 00:12:20.730
at Google that a lot
of Dan's colleagues

00:12:20.730 --> 00:12:23.330
and even people that
he'd never met before

00:12:23.330 --> 00:12:26.870
were incredible in those
first few days, so supportive.

00:12:26.870 --> 00:12:28.440
Everyone was so excited.

00:12:28.440 --> 00:12:32.200
And I think really lent some
great momentum to the project.

00:12:32.200 --> 00:12:38.580
And so then, by the end of the
campaign, we had over $144,000.

00:12:38.580 --> 00:12:40.580
GAIL SIMMONS: Which
translate to how many books?

00:12:40.580 --> 00:12:41.610
LEANNE BROWN: 40,000 books.

00:12:41.610 --> 00:12:42.500
GAIL SIMMONS: 40,000 books.

00:12:42.500 --> 00:12:43.291
LEANNE BROWN: Yeah.

00:12:43.291 --> 00:12:45.210
GAIL SIMMONS: Just to
put that in perspective,

00:12:45.210 --> 00:12:47.251
and the people at
Workman can certainly--

00:12:47.251 --> 00:12:48.250
LEANNE BROWN: Oh my god.

00:12:48.250 --> 00:12:50.320
GAIL SIMMONS: --fill in
the blanks about this.

00:12:50.320 --> 00:12:56.280
But a first run of a cookbook
by someone relatively unknown

00:12:56.280 --> 00:12:57.064
at the time.

00:12:57.064 --> 00:12:57.850
LEANNE BROWN: Completely, yeah.

00:12:57.850 --> 00:13:00.391
GAIL SIMMONS: Now, Leanne Brown
will be in the history books.

00:13:02.430 --> 00:13:04.020
Is sort of unprecedented.

00:13:04.020 --> 00:13:07.680
Who publishes a 40,000 book run?

00:13:07.680 --> 00:13:09.590
Granted you were given
a lot of them away.

00:13:09.590 --> 00:13:15.210
But that is, by any measure,
an extraordinary feat.

00:13:15.210 --> 00:13:17.460
Let alone one that
you knew most of which

00:13:17.460 --> 00:13:19.447
was going to be given away--

00:13:19.447 --> 00:13:20.280
LEANNE BROWN: Right.

00:13:20.280 --> 00:13:21.946
GAIL SIMMONS: --as a
non-profit venture.

00:13:21.946 --> 00:13:24.670
LEANNE BROWN: Well, and that was
what was kind of exciting as we

00:13:24.670 --> 00:13:25.960
were making more
and more money, we

00:13:25.960 --> 00:13:28.220
knew that we were going to
be able to give more away.

00:13:28.220 --> 00:13:30.420
That was kind of
what we had said.

00:13:30.420 --> 00:13:32.670
When I made my little video
I said, the more we raise,

00:13:32.670 --> 00:13:33.753
the more we can give away.

00:13:33.753 --> 00:13:36.540
And we really wanted to do that.

00:13:36.540 --> 00:13:39.130
In the end the
breakdown was, 7,000

00:13:39.130 --> 00:13:41.640
went to our Kickstarter
backers 9,000

00:13:41.640 --> 00:13:44.469
we donated through hundreds
of different profits

00:13:44.469 --> 00:13:45.260
across the country.

00:13:45.260 --> 00:13:47.880
And I can talk a little
bit more about that later.

00:13:47.880 --> 00:13:51.000
And then the balance,
so we had 24,000 left.

00:13:51.000 --> 00:13:53.150
And we wanted to give
away as many as possible.

00:13:53.150 --> 00:13:57.650
But it's expensive to just like
purely donate those things.

00:13:57.650 --> 00:13:59.540
And so what we figured
was, we could still

00:13:59.540 --> 00:14:01.540
get more into people's
hands, if we asked people

00:14:01.540 --> 00:14:02.970
to pay just a
little bit for them.

00:14:02.970 --> 00:14:05.390
So we asked the same
nonprofits, would you guys

00:14:05.390 --> 00:14:07.380
be interested in
purchasing these at cost?

00:14:07.380 --> 00:14:08.840
So about $4 a book.

00:14:08.840 --> 00:14:11.360
And we got an incredible
outpouring of interest

00:14:11.360 --> 00:14:12.360
there as well.

00:14:12.360 --> 00:14:15.592
And so the balance was
24,000 we sold at $4 each

00:14:15.592 --> 00:14:17.050
to those same
non-profits we worked

00:14:17.050 --> 00:14:20.490
with about 600 different
non-profits across the country.

00:14:20.490 --> 00:14:23.710
And they were talking
about, obviously,

00:14:23.710 --> 00:14:26.920
food banks and food
pantries, a lot of schools

00:14:26.920 --> 00:14:30.100
and daycare programs,
senior centers, lots

00:14:30.100 --> 00:14:34.100
of farmers' markets, a lot
of different health care

00:14:34.100 --> 00:14:37.880
organizations, even
some health insurance

00:14:37.880 --> 00:14:39.210
plans were interested in.

00:14:39.210 --> 00:14:41.650
It was fascinating the
sort of groups of people

00:14:41.650 --> 00:14:43.980
who I had never thought about
being interested in this,

00:14:43.980 --> 00:14:47.920
who were saying, this is such an
important issue for my clients.

00:14:47.920 --> 00:14:50.070
It's people that I never
really thought about.

00:14:50.070 --> 00:14:52.660
GAIL SIMMONS: I think that
that brings up a point,

00:14:52.660 --> 00:14:55.733
if I can take a
slight serious turn.

00:14:58.430 --> 00:15:02.370
The scale of the issue
of hunger in America.

00:15:02.370 --> 00:15:10.200
Your book says this, 46 million
people in this country know

00:15:10.200 --> 00:15:10.940
hunger, go to--

00:15:10.940 --> 00:15:11.940
LEANNE BROWN: Right now.

00:15:11.940 --> 00:15:15.430
GAIL SIMMONS: --hungry, or
what's called food insecure.

00:15:15.430 --> 00:15:19.832
So don't know where their
next meal will be from.

00:15:19.832 --> 00:15:21.540
LEANNE BROWN: It's
15% of the population.

00:15:21.540 --> 00:15:21.890
GAIL SIMMONS: Right.

00:15:21.890 --> 00:15:22.640
LEANNE BROWN: Yeah.

00:15:22.640 --> 00:15:24.931
GAIL SIMMONS: By the way,
side note, we're from Canada.

00:15:27.510 --> 00:15:30.100
By far not a perfect country,
but a much smaller country

00:15:30.100 --> 00:15:31.120
by population.

00:15:31.120 --> 00:15:33.390
46 million hungry
people in this country.

00:15:33.390 --> 00:15:38.722
There are only 35 million
people in Canada, full stop.

00:15:38.722 --> 00:15:40.680
LEANNE BROWN: I mean that
was a huge thing when

00:15:40.680 --> 00:15:43.840
I was in grad school, just
that, thinking about that.

00:15:43.840 --> 00:15:46.090
It's difficult to actually
wrap your mind around.

00:15:46.090 --> 00:15:48.990
GAIL SIMMONS: And knowing
that the face of hunger-- that

00:15:48.990 --> 00:15:51.890
sounds like a weird
poster that should

00:15:51.890 --> 00:15:56.699
go on the subway-- but you
don't know what it looks like.

00:15:56.699 --> 00:15:57.490
And to your point--

00:15:57.490 --> 00:15:58.110
LEANNE BROWN: It's so diverse.

00:15:58.110 --> 00:16:00.690
GAIL SIMMONS: --the outpouring
of people that we talked about

00:16:00.690 --> 00:16:05.960
and the places that you
were being contacted by

00:16:05.960 --> 00:16:11.182
were incredibly diverse and from
the corners of our population

00:16:11.182 --> 00:16:12.390
that you would never imagine.

00:16:12.390 --> 00:16:13.960
LEANNE BROWN: Absolutely.

00:16:13.960 --> 00:16:15.580
I mean we all know
that there are so

00:16:15.580 --> 00:16:18.690
many stereotypes about people
who are living with hunger,

00:16:18.690 --> 00:16:20.210
people who are on food stamps.

00:16:20.210 --> 00:16:24.410
But it's 15% of the
population, they're

00:16:24.410 --> 00:16:26.510
as diverse as the
rest of the country.

00:16:26.510 --> 00:16:30.270
And the stories are really
incredible and really moving

00:16:30.270 --> 00:16:31.560
and really important.

00:16:31.560 --> 00:16:33.900
And that's actually
something about this project

00:16:33.900 --> 00:16:35.940
that I probably
should have expected,

00:16:35.940 --> 00:16:41.080
but I never expected sort of
to be as intense and as moving.

00:16:41.080 --> 00:16:43.890
I hear from people daily
who will share things.

00:16:43.890 --> 00:16:45.620
I get a lot of letters
that start with,

00:16:45.620 --> 00:16:49.370
I've never shared this
story with anyone before.

00:16:49.370 --> 00:16:53.970
And I'm so honored
that people trust me

00:16:53.970 --> 00:16:56.250
that see me as someone
who can understand

00:16:56.250 --> 00:16:59.430
their story that is probably
really difficult to tell.

00:16:59.430 --> 00:17:05.680
But I also I feel an intense
need to tell those stories too.

00:17:05.680 --> 00:17:09.212
And a real desire
to in small ways

00:17:09.212 --> 00:17:10.920
try to make the world
a little bit safer,

00:17:10.920 --> 00:17:12.943
so that people can feel
more comfortable sharing

00:17:12.943 --> 00:17:13.859
their stories as well.

00:17:13.859 --> 00:17:15.660
And especially to
the people that they

00:17:15.660 --> 00:17:18.762
work with and their family and
their friends because you know

00:17:18.762 --> 00:17:20.720
we're talking about 15%
of the population who's

00:17:20.720 --> 00:17:22.420
dealing with this right now.

00:17:22.420 --> 00:17:24.290
Think about over the
course of your life.

00:17:24.290 --> 00:17:27.520
We all know someone,
or even many people,

00:17:27.520 --> 00:17:29.010
who have dealt
with these issues.

00:17:29.010 --> 00:17:30.780
And it's a very hidden problem.

00:17:30.780 --> 00:17:36.610
And it shouldn't be because
shame festers in places

00:17:36.610 --> 00:17:38.690
where there's no light
when we don't talk

00:17:38.690 --> 00:17:40.050
to people about these things.

00:17:40.050 --> 00:17:42.530
GAIL SIMMONS: And becomes
in itself a cycle.

00:17:42.530 --> 00:17:44.500
LEANNE BROWN: Yes

00:17:44.500 --> 00:17:47.050
GAIL SIMMONS: Being able
to eat with integrity

00:17:47.050 --> 00:17:48.970
I think about a lot.

00:17:48.970 --> 00:17:54.130
And I think this is a viable
tool by which people can do so.

00:17:54.130 --> 00:17:54.880
LEANNE BROWN: Yes.

00:17:54.880 --> 00:17:58.160
I mean I hope that it can be
useful for a lot of people.

00:17:58.160 --> 00:18:01.740
It's certainly not going
to work for everyone.

00:18:01.740 --> 00:18:04.480
There's no tool I think that can
work for absolutely everyone.

00:18:04.480 --> 00:18:06.510
But I hope that this is of use.

00:18:06.510 --> 00:18:08.965
I know that it's of
use to a lot of people.

00:18:08.965 --> 00:18:11.340
GAIL SIMMONS: So tell us where
you are now with the book.

00:18:11.340 --> 00:18:16.750
You gave away and sold
those first 40,000.

00:18:16.750 --> 00:18:17.650
And then?

00:18:17.650 --> 00:18:20.130
LEANNE BROWN: Well, and then
it was during the Kickstarter

00:18:20.130 --> 00:18:22.700
that I heard from a few
different publishers, which

00:18:22.700 --> 00:18:25.040
was really surprising
to me at first.

00:18:25.040 --> 00:18:27.590
And not because I thought,
well, I'm the best, Dan

00:18:27.590 --> 00:18:30.502
and I are brilliant
at publishing,

00:18:30.502 --> 00:18:31.960
we just want to do
this on our own.

00:18:31.960 --> 00:18:33.334
It was just that
we never thought

00:18:33.334 --> 00:18:37.520
that any publisher would want
to help us give away cookbooks.

00:18:37.520 --> 00:18:40.010
They're in the business
of the opposite of that.

00:18:40.010 --> 00:18:43.220
So I just never looked
for a publisher.

00:18:43.220 --> 00:18:45.910
And so I ended up meeting up
with the incredible people

00:18:45.910 --> 00:18:48.210
at Workman Publishing,
many of whom are here

00:18:48.210 --> 00:18:50.260
today to support me.

00:18:50.260 --> 00:18:54.000
And they said we
love your cookbook,

00:18:54.000 --> 00:18:56.450
but we and we want to help
you take this project further.

00:18:56.450 --> 00:18:58.672
We love the giveaway idea.

00:18:58.672 --> 00:18:59.880
This is what we're all about.

00:18:59.880 --> 00:19:01.546
And we want to help
you take it further.

00:19:01.546 --> 00:19:03.720
I was like, yes, please.

00:19:03.720 --> 00:19:05.940
Not only because, obviously,
that's just a good idea,

00:19:05.940 --> 00:19:08.120
but also because
we had just managed

00:19:08.120 --> 00:19:11.940
to distribute 40,000 books and
never wanted to do that again.

00:19:11.940 --> 00:19:13.600
Actually it before
all that happened.

00:19:13.600 --> 00:19:13.970
GAIL SIMMONS: From
your apartment--

00:19:13.970 --> 00:19:15.450
LEANNE BROWN: I was
just terrified about it

00:19:15.450 --> 00:19:16.158
at that point it.

00:19:16.158 --> 00:19:18.129
I was just like, ugh.

00:19:18.129 --> 00:19:19.920
GAIL SIMMONS: But doing
it with a publisher

00:19:19.920 --> 00:19:22.050
will give you an enormous
amount of infrastructure.

00:19:22.050 --> 00:19:23.530
LEANNE BROWN: Let the people
who know what they're doing,

00:19:23.530 --> 00:19:24.260
do their thing.

00:19:24.260 --> 00:19:25.682
Yes.

00:19:25.682 --> 00:19:26.566
There are experts--

00:19:26.566 --> 00:19:27.008
GAIL SIMMONS:
That's what they do.

00:19:27.008 --> 00:19:28.091
LEANNE BROWN: --out there.

00:19:28.091 --> 00:19:29.170
Yes.

00:19:29.170 --> 00:19:31.290
So it's been incredible.

00:19:31.290 --> 00:19:34.550
So what we did was, we created a
second edition of the cookbook.

00:19:34.550 --> 00:19:38.420
So that gave me the opportunity
to kind of look at the book

00:19:38.420 --> 00:19:41.420
again because it had
sort of melded out

00:19:41.420 --> 00:19:43.650
of this thesis and then
some other information.

00:19:43.650 --> 00:19:45.210
And then I'd added
some new recipes

00:19:45.210 --> 00:19:48.340
through the Kickstarter, gotten
some cool stories from people

00:19:48.340 --> 00:19:50.730
that had written to me.

00:19:50.730 --> 00:19:52.470
I'd been able to
improve it a little bit,

00:19:52.470 --> 00:19:54.670
but this is another
opportunity to fill

00:19:54.670 --> 00:19:56.984
in a lot more of the holes,
address some of the things

00:19:56.984 --> 00:19:58.650
that people said, we
actually like this.

00:19:58.650 --> 00:20:03.779
Like all the information
about how to shop,

00:20:03.779 --> 00:20:05.820
like what are some strategies
for what you should

00:20:05.820 --> 00:20:08.030
have in your kitchen, and how
you can get food on the table

00:20:08.030 --> 00:20:08.530
quickly.

00:20:08.530 --> 00:20:09.800
All these kinds of things.

00:20:09.800 --> 00:20:11.580
That tends to be the
part of the cookbook

00:20:11.580 --> 00:20:13.370
that I personally skip.

00:20:13.370 --> 00:20:15.634
So I was like, uh, people
aren't that into this.

00:20:15.634 --> 00:20:17.800
It turned out that people
were incredibly interested

00:20:17.800 --> 00:20:18.633
in that information.

00:20:18.633 --> 00:20:21.526
And so I added a
lot more of that.

00:20:21.526 --> 00:20:22.900
I think we've
really improved it.

00:20:22.900 --> 00:20:26.510
And so that's what came
out this past July.

00:20:26.510 --> 00:20:29.200
And for every one
that's sold, not just

00:20:29.200 --> 00:20:30.620
on my little
website, where people

00:20:30.620 --> 00:20:33.470
ha to go to get it before,
but now in bookstores,

00:20:33.470 --> 00:20:36.120
everywhere, online,
everywhere, we

00:20:36.120 --> 00:20:39.400
are donating one for one
for every single one.

00:20:39.400 --> 00:20:41.152
And that's going to
be as long as it's--

00:20:41.152 --> 00:20:42.610
GAIL SIMMONS: How
do you distribute

00:20:42.610 --> 00:20:43.840
the ones that are given away?

00:20:43.840 --> 00:20:45.320
LEANNE BROWN: Right.

00:20:45.320 --> 00:20:46.972
That's the other exciting thing.

00:20:46.972 --> 00:20:48.930
With the publisher we
had even more opportunity

00:20:48.930 --> 00:20:49.780
for partnership.

00:20:49.780 --> 00:20:53.650
So our giveaway partner
is located in Cincinnati.

00:20:53.650 --> 00:20:55.290
They're called, Access Wireless.

00:20:55.290 --> 00:20:58.310
And they warehouse all the
books and they send them

00:20:58.310 --> 00:21:03.860
out to the different nonprofits
and to the Feeding America Food

00:21:03.860 --> 00:21:06.160
Bank system, as well as
to a lot of their clients.

00:21:06.160 --> 00:21:10.830
So Access Wireless is a
provider of the government

00:21:10.830 --> 00:21:13.770
funded lifeline program, which
has been around since the '80s.

00:21:13.770 --> 00:21:16.600
And the idea behind
it when it started

00:21:16.600 --> 00:21:19.730
was that no one should ever
have to choose between paying

00:21:19.730 --> 00:21:21.765
for food or paying for a phone.

00:21:21.765 --> 00:21:23.640
GAIL SIMMONS: And in
the '80s, let's remember

00:21:23.640 --> 00:21:24.707
what phones looked like.

00:21:24.707 --> 00:21:25.790
LEANNE BROWN: Yeah, right.

00:21:25.790 --> 00:21:26.400
Exactly.

