tend to be sort
of not as excited

00:32:00.910 --> 00:32:02.320
about leftovers the next day.

00:32:02.320 --> 00:32:02.440
GAIL SIMMONS: Oh no.

00:32:02.440 --> 00:32:04.023
I'm actually very
suspicious of people

00:32:04.023 --> 00:32:05.640
who don't like leftovers.

00:32:05.640 --> 00:32:06.786
I'm sorry, Leanne.

00:32:06.786 --> 00:32:08.660
We're going to agree to
disagree on this one.

00:32:08.660 --> 00:32:10.076
LEANNE BROWN: I'm
happy with them,

00:32:10.076 --> 00:32:13.834
but I have to do something
different to them.

00:32:13.834 --> 00:32:15.250
GAIL SIMMONS: I'll
allow you that.

00:32:15.250 --> 00:32:16.625
LEANNE BROWN: That
just sometimes

00:32:16.625 --> 00:32:17.831
means putting an egg on top.

00:32:17.831 --> 00:32:20.330
GAIL SIMMONS: We have a saying
at the food and wine offices,

00:32:20.330 --> 00:32:21.610
everything is better
with an egg on top.

00:32:21.610 --> 00:32:23.030
LEANNE BROWN: Yeah, right.

00:32:23.030 --> 00:32:24.010
Drooling out.

00:32:24.010 --> 00:32:25.547
GAIL SIMMONS: Yes.

00:32:25.547 --> 00:32:27.630
And there's a lot of great
information about eggs.

00:32:27.630 --> 00:32:29.130
And I could talk
about eggs all day.

00:32:29.130 --> 00:32:30.950
But there's a lot
of simple examples,

00:32:30.950 --> 00:32:32.884
like eggs that I
think become so handy.

00:32:32.884 --> 00:32:33.800
Yogurt is one of them.

00:32:33.800 --> 00:32:36.010
I love your discussion
about yogurt

00:32:36.010 --> 00:32:37.760
because I think it's
something that people

00:32:37.760 --> 00:32:39.110
don't think about a lot.

00:32:39.110 --> 00:32:40.026
LEANNE BROWN: Totally.

00:32:40.026 --> 00:32:43.230
And that actually came almost
directly out of this work

00:32:43.230 --> 00:32:45.410
that I did during my degree.

00:32:45.410 --> 00:32:50.170
I got to do grocery store tours
with a lot of families who

00:32:50.170 --> 00:32:52.100
are part of the WIC program.

00:32:52.100 --> 00:32:53.240
And we would so often--

00:32:53.240 --> 00:32:53.935
GAIL SIMMONS: WIC is--

00:32:53.935 --> 00:32:55.820
LEANNE BROWN: I'm sorry, yes,
the Women with Infant Children

00:32:55.820 --> 00:32:56.320
program.

00:32:56.320 --> 00:33:01.211
So it's special food
vouchers basically of foods

00:33:01.211 --> 00:33:02.710
that are specifically
good for women

00:33:02.710 --> 00:33:05.410
who are pregnant with children
up to the age of five.

00:33:05.410 --> 00:33:07.884
GAIL SIMMONS: It's subsidies
as part of the bigger--

00:33:07.884 --> 00:33:08.800
LEANNE BROWN: Exactly.

00:33:08.800 --> 00:33:11.804
And so there's a big
dairy component, actually.

00:33:11.804 --> 00:33:13.220
And that became
really interesting

00:33:13.220 --> 00:33:15.428
because of course some people
are lactose intolerant.

00:33:15.428 --> 00:33:17.950
And it was always like,
OK, how do you use this?

00:33:17.950 --> 00:33:19.950
But we always have such
a fascinating discussion

00:33:19.950 --> 00:33:21.540
at the dairy case.

00:33:21.540 --> 00:33:23.750
And everyone would
say, oh, I love yogurt.

00:33:23.750 --> 00:33:25.760
I love giving these
yogurts to my kids.

00:33:25.760 --> 00:33:28.240
And it was usually
those tiny little ones

00:33:28.240 --> 00:33:34.690
that are unfortunately full
of sugar and almost as bad

00:33:34.690 --> 00:33:36.370
as an ice cream a
lot of the time.

00:33:36.370 --> 00:33:39.010
And as I was sort of having to
deliver this sort of bad news,

00:33:39.010 --> 00:33:43.060
I was like, how can I
like soften the blow here?

00:33:43.060 --> 00:33:47.470
And because yogurt is a really,
really nutritious and fantastic

00:33:47.470 --> 00:33:48.200
ingredient.

00:33:48.200 --> 00:33:50.630
It's just that it's
really good when it's

00:33:50.630 --> 00:33:52.110
like the good plain yogurt.

00:33:52.110 --> 00:33:56.320
These like little fancified,
little mini whatevers

00:33:56.320 --> 00:33:57.870
are not so hot for you.

00:33:57.870 --> 00:34:00.680
And so I would always be
trying to explain like,

00:34:00.680 --> 00:34:02.410
buy the large tub of yogurt.

00:34:02.410 --> 00:34:06.450
Not only can you make your own
flavors at home if you like,

00:34:06.450 --> 00:34:09.780
you can throw in some
blueberries, a tablespoon

00:34:09.780 --> 00:34:11.432
of jam, whatever you like.

00:34:11.432 --> 00:34:12.710
GAIL SIMMONS: As seen on page.

00:34:12.710 --> 00:34:14.880
LEANNE BROWN: Yeah, you can make
your own key lime pie version

00:34:14.880 --> 00:34:15.380
a home.

00:34:15.380 --> 00:34:19.250
It's not that
difficult. But also

00:34:19.250 --> 00:34:20.719
it becomes then
an ingredient too.

00:34:20.719 --> 00:34:22.790
It something I would
always love explaining.

00:34:22.790 --> 00:34:25.340
Greek yogurt is really just
strange regular yogurt.

00:34:25.340 --> 00:34:26.699
And that's something you can do.

00:34:26.699 --> 00:34:30.217
And you can make all kinds
of savory sauces, make Raita.

00:34:30.217 --> 00:34:31.300
GAIL SIMMONS: Dips using--

00:34:31.300 --> 00:34:32.823
LEANNE BROWN: Yeah, tzatziki.

00:34:32.823 --> 00:34:34.239
GAIL SIMMONS: --as
a substitution.

00:34:34.239 --> 00:34:35.655
LEANNE BROWN: Right
and that's why

00:34:35.655 --> 00:34:36.850
there's quite a few I think.

00:34:36.850 --> 00:34:39.030
The zucchini muffins
recipe uses yogurt.

00:34:39.030 --> 00:34:42.570
And just yogurt is an item that
you should have in the fridge.

00:34:42.570 --> 00:34:47.139
And so I tried to design as many
of the recipes as possible that

00:34:47.139 --> 00:34:48.889
use those sort of
really basic things

00:34:48.889 --> 00:34:50.722
that you might use for
a snack, but then you

00:34:50.722 --> 00:34:53.090
can use them in different ways.

00:34:53.090 --> 00:34:53.980
So, yeah.

00:34:53.980 --> 00:34:56.230
GAIL SIMMONS: What's your
favorite recipe in the book?

00:34:56.230 --> 00:35:00.020
If You had to make something
every day, what would you make?

00:35:00.020 --> 00:35:01.520
What's the recipe
you love the most?

00:35:01.520 --> 00:35:03.800
LEANNE BROWN: It's
the Chana Masala,

00:35:03.800 --> 00:35:06.690
which is a chickpea curry.

00:35:06.690 --> 00:35:09.560
And that's because when
I was in university,

00:35:09.560 --> 00:35:11.890
I was totally obsessed
with Indian food.

00:35:11.890 --> 00:35:12.835
I absolutely loved it.

00:35:12.835 --> 00:35:14.210
And it really took
me a long time

00:35:14.210 --> 00:35:15.709
to figure out how
to make it myself.

00:35:15.709 --> 00:35:17.550
And I had a ton
of trial and error

00:35:17.550 --> 00:35:20.630
and just failed miserably
many, many times.

00:35:20.630 --> 00:35:22.730
But because I
loved it so much, I

00:35:22.730 --> 00:35:25.130
continued to try to
make it and my friends

00:35:25.130 --> 00:35:30.470
and I had this one coffee
shop that we would always

00:35:30.470 --> 00:35:31.020
hang out at.

00:35:31.020 --> 00:35:32.436
And it was a coffee
shop that also

00:35:32.436 --> 00:35:35.040
had all kinds of
Pakistani food, which is

00:35:35.040 --> 00:35:36.680
a sort of strange combination.

00:35:36.680 --> 00:35:38.450
But it was awesome.

00:35:38.450 --> 00:35:41.240
And they had Chana Masala.

00:35:41.240 --> 00:35:42.990
And we were totally
obsessed with it.

00:35:42.990 --> 00:35:46.121
And so I had to figure
out how to make it.

00:35:46.121 --> 00:35:47.620
It's really not
that difficult. It's

00:35:47.620 --> 00:35:50.020
just that you need to
sort of toast the spices

00:35:50.020 --> 00:35:51.220
and layer the flavors.

00:35:51.220 --> 00:35:53.240
And I finally figured that out.

00:35:53.240 --> 00:35:56.890
And I was just so excited to
share this with my friends.

00:35:56.890 --> 00:35:59.340
And it's also something that
takes only about 20 minutes

00:35:59.340 --> 00:36:00.020
to put together.

00:36:00.020 --> 00:36:02.870
And it so transforms just
regular old chickpeas

00:36:02.870 --> 00:36:06.570
into this most unctuous,
most incredibly comforting

00:36:06.570 --> 00:36:07.750
beautiful dish.

00:36:07.750 --> 00:36:09.820
GAIL SIMMONS: And it costs what?

00:36:09.820 --> 00:36:12.080
LEANNE BROWN: I think it's
like $3 for that amount.

00:36:12.080 --> 00:36:14.216
It's so cheap.

00:36:14.216 --> 00:36:16.590
Which is, of course, amazing
because we were all students

00:36:16.590 --> 00:36:17.449
and had no money.

00:36:17.449 --> 00:36:19.490
And we would spend our
money at this coffee shop,

00:36:19.490 --> 00:36:21.930
but it would be a lot better
if we could make it at home.

00:36:21.930 --> 00:36:24.040
And it was one of the
first times I really

00:36:24.040 --> 00:36:28.040
had that satisfying feeling of
sharing a recipe with people

00:36:28.040 --> 00:36:31.050
and people say, I made
that and I really loved it.

00:36:31.050 --> 00:36:32.930
And my friends will
still tell me to this day

00:36:32.930 --> 00:36:35.250
that that's comfort food
that they make for themselves

00:36:35.250 --> 00:36:36.640
on a regular basis.

00:36:36.640 --> 00:36:40.120
And to me that's just so
amazing and such an honor

00:36:40.120 --> 00:36:44.352
to be in someone's home in a
small way by giving a recipe.

00:36:44.352 --> 00:36:46.643
GAIL SIMMONS: So we're all
making Chana Masala tonight,

00:36:46.643 --> 00:36:47.430
right?

00:36:47.430 --> 00:36:49.450
I am.

00:36:49.450 --> 00:36:53.090
Before we take some questions
from the audience, last thing.

00:36:53.090 --> 00:36:55.380
What is next for
"Good and Cheap?"

00:36:55.380 --> 00:36:59.870
If you could have your own way
and do whatever and take it

00:36:59.870 --> 00:37:01.370
to the next level,
what would it be?

00:37:01.370 --> 00:37:02.411
LEANNE BROWN: Oh my gosh.

00:37:02.411 --> 00:37:06.100
For "Good and Cheap," well,
so we're going to keep going.

00:37:06.100 --> 00:37:08.020
I think there's
incredible partnership

00:37:08.020 --> 00:37:09.950
possibilities available.

00:37:09.950 --> 00:37:11.575
But my big focus,
and I don't know

00:37:11.575 --> 00:37:12.950
exactly how I'm
going to do this,

00:37:12.950 --> 00:37:15.290
but is to share the stories
that people have been

00:37:15.290 --> 00:37:17.180
sharing with me in some way.

00:37:17.180 --> 00:37:21.552
In a way that really honors
them and that will make

00:37:21.552 --> 00:37:24.010
people want to read them and
pay attention to them as well.

00:37:24.010 --> 00:37:26.020
And so I'm not sure how
that project will work,

00:37:26.020 --> 00:37:29.760
whether it'll be a
podcast or a video series.

00:37:29.760 --> 00:37:33.120
But I think that's a really
important component of this

00:37:33.120 --> 00:37:35.940
because it's not
just about the food,

00:37:35.940 --> 00:37:38.410
but it's about the people
who are making this food.

00:37:38.410 --> 00:37:42.950
And I feel like I have a
responsibility to do that.

00:37:42.950 --> 00:37:46.250
GAIL SIMMONS: Then there's
a part B to this question.

00:37:46.250 --> 00:37:48.320
I'm getting kicked off stage.

00:37:48.320 --> 00:37:50.000
How can we help?

00:37:50.000 --> 00:37:51.240
LEANNE BROWN: Oh my goodness.

00:37:51.240 --> 00:37:55.250
Well, I guess tell
people about the stuff.

00:37:55.250 --> 00:37:56.946
Cook.

00:37:56.946 --> 00:37:58.070
GAIL SIMMONS: Buy the book.

00:38:01.260 --> 00:38:04.480
LEANNE BROWN: Learn more
about the Food Stamps program.

00:38:04.480 --> 00:38:06.970
Vote for people who
you think actually

00:38:06.970 --> 00:38:08.650
care about these
issues and are not

00:38:08.650 --> 00:38:11.080
going to continue
to defund them.

00:38:11.080 --> 00:38:13.125
Very, very, very important.

00:38:13.125 --> 00:38:15.250
GAIL SIMMONS: You can find
out who those people are

00:38:15.250 --> 00:38:15.900
pretty easily, actually.

00:38:15.900 --> 00:38:16.870
LEANNE BROWN: Pretty easily.

00:38:16.870 --> 00:38:19.050
GAIL SIMMONS: There's a, now
I'm forgetting the name of it.

00:38:19.050 --> 00:38:20.540
There's a website
that just launched.

00:38:20.540 --> 00:38:22.248
OK, I'm going to get
back to you on that.

00:38:22.248 --> 00:38:24.080
But that rates the
Congress people

00:38:24.080 --> 00:38:28.290
in your constituency on
issues surrounding the Farm

00:38:28.290 --> 00:38:33.540
Bill and Child Nutrition Act.

00:38:33.540 --> 00:38:38.740
This, in the biggest way I
think, is a policy issue.

00:38:38.740 --> 00:38:39.240
But--

00:38:39.240 --> 00:38:39.750
LEANNE BROWN: Agree.

00:38:39.750 --> 00:38:41.166
GAIL SIMMONS: --we
all have voices

00:38:41.166 --> 00:38:45.080
and we all can improve the
health of our communities

00:38:45.080 --> 00:38:46.834
by cooking good and cheap.

00:38:46.834 --> 00:38:48.000
LEANNE BROWN: Yeah, exactly.

00:38:48.000 --> 00:38:50.220
I guess just be confident
in your own lives.

00:38:50.220 --> 00:38:53.420
And know that cooking
is not something

00:38:53.420 --> 00:38:54.420
that's only for experts.

00:38:54.420 --> 00:38:56.086
It's something that
absolutely all of us

00:38:56.086 --> 00:38:59.050
can do, and get a lot
of enjoyment out of,

00:38:59.050 --> 00:39:02.581
and improve our lives
in just small ways.

00:39:02.581 --> 00:39:04.080
GAIL SIMMONS: Thank
you so, so much.

00:39:04.080 --> 00:39:05.204
Thanks everyone for coming.

00:39:08.257 --> 00:39:10.090
LEANNE BROWN: Do we
have time for questions?

00:39:10.090 --> 00:39:11.410
OK, wonderful.

