00:39:42.852 --> 00:39:44.346
AUDIENCE: Hi, thanks for coming.

00:39:44.346 --> 00:39:45.280
Read your book.

00:39:45.280 --> 00:39:47.801
You had a lot of really
good ideas in it.

00:39:47.801 --> 00:39:50.965
But I noticed this earlier
you made a quip like,

00:39:50.965 --> 00:39:53.090
oh, people think when
they're going on food stamps,

00:39:53.090 --> 00:39:54.400
all they're going to be
able to eat is ramen.

00:39:54.400 --> 00:39:54.790
LEANNE BROWN: Right.

00:39:54.790 --> 00:39:56.070
AUDIENCE: And that's
not really true.

00:39:56.070 --> 00:39:57.640
Would you say it's more
accurate that if someone's

00:39:57.640 --> 00:39:59.135
going on food
stamps, they're going

00:39:59.135 --> 00:40:01.050
to be eating a lot less meat?

00:40:01.050 --> 00:40:03.190
And if that is
accurate, do you think

00:40:03.190 --> 00:40:06.730
that would be a cultural shift
for your average food stamp

00:40:06.730 --> 00:40:07.909
recipient?

00:40:07.909 --> 00:40:10.450
LEANNE BROWN: So I don't think
there is an average food stamp

00:40:10.450 --> 00:40:10.950
recipient.

00:40:10.950 --> 00:40:15.939
So that's not something
that I sort of feel

00:40:15.939 --> 00:40:17.230
totally comfortable going with.

00:40:17.230 --> 00:40:23.460
But definitely I think
it's naturally much cheaper

00:40:23.460 --> 00:40:24.816
to eat less meat.

00:40:24.816 --> 00:40:26.190
And you'll notice
in the book you

00:40:26.190 --> 00:40:28.650
know it's not a
vegetarian book, but there

00:40:28.650 --> 00:40:30.440
isn't that much meat in it.

00:40:30.440 --> 00:40:32.570
And that's just for
practical reasons.

00:40:32.570 --> 00:40:37.260
And because if you use meat in
sort of more as a flavoring,

00:40:37.260 --> 00:40:39.840
rather than as the
center of the dish,

00:40:39.840 --> 00:40:43.205
you can still have it as a
part of your diet without it

00:40:43.205 --> 00:40:44.210
sort of taking over.

00:40:44.210 --> 00:40:45.890
I think the fact is
that a lot of people

00:40:45.890 --> 00:40:49.879
are very used to eating meat,
who maybe have had something

00:40:49.879 --> 00:40:51.420
happen in their life
that has made it

00:40:51.420 --> 00:40:54.405
so that they are
having a change,

00:40:54.405 --> 00:40:56.530
having to go on food stamps
say for the first time,

00:40:56.530 --> 00:40:58.630
that yes you might sort
of start out buying

00:40:58.630 --> 00:41:00.680
your regular amount of meat.

00:41:00.680 --> 00:41:02.660
And maybe discover
that as a result,

00:41:02.660 --> 00:41:05.160
you don't have enough
left over to eat enough.

00:41:05.160 --> 00:41:08.470
So that would
probably be a shift.

00:41:08.470 --> 00:41:12.910
But there are so many
cultures that meat is not

00:41:12.910 --> 00:41:13.690
half the plate.

00:41:13.690 --> 00:41:16.280
It's usually like
1/15 of the plate.

00:41:16.280 --> 00:41:18.359
It's just sort of
a part of the dish.

00:41:18.359 --> 00:41:19.900
And so it's something
that's actually

00:41:19.900 --> 00:41:22.275
pretty unique in the world
that we eat the amount of meat

00:41:22.275 --> 00:41:24.010
that we do.

00:41:24.010 --> 00:41:26.010
I think it's not about
sort of thinking, oh man,

00:41:26.010 --> 00:41:27.218
I don't get any meat anymore.

00:41:27.218 --> 00:41:30.160
It's about replacing that with
stuff that you're excited about

00:41:30.160 --> 00:41:31.360
and giving it a try.

00:41:31.360 --> 00:41:33.954
And then hopefully
realizing that the food

00:41:33.954 --> 00:41:36.370
that you're going to eat is
just as satisfying and just as

00:41:36.370 --> 00:41:36.890
interesting.

00:41:36.890 --> 00:41:39.440
And for me fruits and
vegetables are actually

00:41:39.440 --> 00:41:42.670
a lot more exciting and
hold a lot more potential

00:41:42.670 --> 00:41:45.210
of interesting flavor
than the meat really does.

00:41:45.210 --> 00:41:49.620
And so when you create menus and
food with fruits and vegetables

00:41:49.620 --> 00:41:51.340
as the organizing
principle, I think

00:41:51.340 --> 00:41:53.500
you're going to be
really excited by it.

00:41:53.500 --> 00:41:56.389
GAIL SIMMONS: And from a
health standpoint, better off.

00:41:56.389 --> 00:41:57.180
LEANNE BROWN: Yeah.

00:41:57.180 --> 00:41:58.020
GAIL SIMMONS: Most
likely to right?

00:41:58.020 --> 00:41:58.811
LEANNE BROWN: Yeah.

00:41:58.811 --> 00:42:01.850
We all know we need more
fruits and vegetables.

00:42:01.850 --> 00:42:04.329
GAIL SIMMONS: Protein Is
not the same thing as meat.

00:42:04.329 --> 00:42:05.620
LEANNE BROWN: Eggs are protein.

00:42:05.620 --> 00:42:08.220
GAIL SIMMONS: Right.

00:42:08.220 --> 00:42:09.580
And beans are protein.

00:42:09.580 --> 00:42:12.205
And there's a lot of ways to get
great protein without focusing

00:42:12.205 --> 00:42:12.704
on meat.

00:42:12.704 --> 00:42:13.220
I think.

00:42:13.220 --> 00:42:16.111
And you discuss that a
lot in the book actually.

00:42:16.111 --> 00:42:17.550
LEANNE BROWN: Hey, Eric.

00:42:17.550 --> 00:42:18.520
ERIC: Hey.

00:42:18.520 --> 00:42:21.060
Any thoughts on how the
food industry could help

00:42:21.060 --> 00:42:22.260
meet these goals as well?

00:42:22.260 --> 00:42:23.260
Changes they could make.

00:42:23.260 --> 00:42:25.580
For instance, I know
that sometimes people

00:42:25.580 --> 00:42:27.970
who are low on money
are also low on time.

00:42:27.970 --> 00:42:29.510
And cooking from
scratch takes time.

00:42:29.510 --> 00:42:31.730
I'm a big Trader Joe's,
not for the prepared food

00:42:31.730 --> 00:42:34.350
because they kind of like
take a whole butternut squash

00:42:34.350 --> 00:42:36.350
and cut it into
little cubes for me.

00:42:36.350 --> 00:42:38.300
Do you have any other thoughts
that have come up in your work

00:42:38.300 --> 00:42:40.341
around how the industry
can help meet you halfway

00:42:40.341 --> 00:42:43.100
in getting people
to do more cooking.

00:42:43.100 --> 00:42:46.410
LEANNE BROWN: I think it's
a great point you bring up.

00:42:46.410 --> 00:42:48.770
I really like that as
well, like those sorts

00:42:48.770 --> 00:42:52.244
of taking basic foods, and
just half preparing them.

00:42:52.244 --> 00:42:53.702
Not going the full
way where you're

00:42:53.702 --> 00:42:56.090
getting your frozen samosas.

00:42:56.090 --> 00:42:58.450
But the cubed butternut squash.

00:42:58.450 --> 00:43:01.330
The problem is often that those
also come with a cost increase,

00:43:01.330 --> 00:43:01.830
right?

00:43:01.830 --> 00:43:04.130
Because it's like
the bags of spinach

00:43:04.130 --> 00:43:05.762
that are prewashed
and beautiful.

00:43:05.762 --> 00:43:07.720
They're double the price
of a bunch of spinach.

00:43:07.720 --> 00:43:10.710
And I mean that's one of
those basic tips is usually

00:43:10.710 --> 00:43:12.970
the more work you
have to do to it,

00:43:12.970 --> 00:43:14.740
the cheaper it's going to be.

00:43:14.740 --> 00:43:18.830
But if there is a way to sort
of to use scale to make it so

00:43:18.830 --> 00:43:21.980
those are more accessible,
then absolutely.

00:43:21.980 --> 00:43:24.334
Gail, do you want to talk
about the grocery store

00:43:24.334 --> 00:43:25.500
that you were talking about?

00:43:25.500 --> 00:43:27.440
GAIL SIMMONS: Yeah.

00:43:27.440 --> 00:43:31.930
Quickly, there was a man
who worked at Trader Joe's

00:43:31.930 --> 00:43:34.950
for 30 years and he was the
president by the time he left.

00:43:34.950 --> 00:43:40.370
And he left a few years ago to
start a company called, Daily

00:43:40.370 --> 00:43:41.760
Table, DailyTable.org.

00:43:41.760 --> 00:43:44.300
You can read about it.

00:43:44.300 --> 00:43:46.650
And right now it's sort of
in beta in Massachusetts,

00:43:46.650 --> 00:43:50.440
in Dorchester, Massachusetts.

00:43:50.440 --> 00:43:57.600
It is a grocery store that
takes in all of the almost

00:43:57.600 --> 00:44:02.880
at the point of not being able
to sell produce and perishable

00:44:02.880 --> 00:44:07.482
food from grocery stores and
retailers across the country

00:44:07.482 --> 00:44:08.690
and brings it to their store.

00:44:08.690 --> 00:44:11.500
So their shelves are
constantly being turned over

00:44:11.500 --> 00:44:15.720
and they buy smaller amounts of
stuff that may be in two days

00:44:15.720 --> 00:44:18.960
from now, a big grocery chain
wouldn't be able to sell.

00:44:18.960 --> 00:44:21.980
And sells it at
deep, deep discounts.

00:44:21.980 --> 00:44:24.360
And they open in food desert.

00:44:24.360 --> 00:44:28.300
They open in communities
that don't have access

00:44:28.300 --> 00:44:29.560
to other grocery stores.

00:44:29.560 --> 00:44:33.080
And so that thinking,
that idea I think--

00:44:33.080 --> 00:44:36.050
and I have every
ounce of confidence

00:44:36.050 --> 00:44:37.590
that this model
will really take off

00:44:37.590 --> 00:44:40.490
and he'll be able to build a
chain across the country of it

00:44:40.490 --> 00:44:46.350
because it's extraordinary--
it has allowed people

00:44:46.350 --> 00:44:50.560
on limited budgets of
any kind to have access

00:44:50.560 --> 00:44:52.390
to fresh fruits or
vegetables in a way

00:44:52.390 --> 00:44:53.210
that they never have before.

00:44:53.210 --> 00:44:54.751
Because the other
piece of the puzzle

00:44:54.751 --> 00:44:57.640
that we've all sort of skirted
around and talked about that's

00:44:57.640 --> 00:45:02.030
so connected and there's so many
sides to this is food waste.

00:45:02.030 --> 00:45:04.560
And that's also part of the
problem, that we as a nation

00:45:04.560 --> 00:45:07.410
are wasting 30% of the
food that we produce.

00:45:07.410 --> 00:45:10.310
And that has to change in order
for costs to come down as well.

00:45:10.310 --> 00:45:10.460
LEANNE BROWN: Right.

00:45:10.460 --> 00:45:12.459
Well, I mean that's
actually why the Food Stamps

00:45:12.459 --> 00:45:15.140
program came to be.

00:45:15.140 --> 00:45:19.800
Was actually because of
the crisis in America

00:45:19.800 --> 00:45:21.855
there is so much food
available, but it's not

00:45:21.855 --> 00:45:22.980
going to where it's needed.

00:45:22.980 --> 00:45:24.090
GAIL SIMMONS: And
that's still the issue.

00:45:24.090 --> 00:45:25.465
The issue is not
that there isn't

00:45:25.465 --> 00:45:27.440
enough food in this country.

00:45:27.440 --> 00:45:28.380
LEANNE BROWN: It's a
distribution problem.

00:45:28.380 --> 00:45:30.463
GAIL SIMMONS: It's a
distribution issues, exactly.

00:45:30.463 --> 00:45:34.186
And it's a government subsidy
issue to some extent as well.

