00:47:41.900 --> 00:47:44.590
and channel to learn about.

00:47:44.590 --> 00:47:46.290
You are inspiring us.

00:47:46.290 --> 00:47:47.170
No, in truth.

00:47:47.170 --> 00:47:49.390
Thank you so much.

00:47:49.390 --> 00:47:50.890
LEANNE BROWN: Thank you.

00:47:50.890 --> 00:47:52.880
GAIL SIMMONS: One more question?

00:47:52.880 --> 00:47:54.650
AUDIENCE: Hi, thanks
for coming again.

00:47:54.650 --> 00:47:57.290
I was just wondering if you
had a specific audience in mind

00:47:57.290 --> 00:47:58.900
when you were
writing the cookbook.

00:47:58.900 --> 00:48:01.680
More specifically, whether it
was for singles or for people

00:48:01.680 --> 00:48:05.040
supporting families
because as a single person,

00:48:05.040 --> 00:48:07.620
I find it difficult
to go grocery shopping

00:48:07.620 --> 00:48:09.490
and difficult to
cook for one person.

00:48:09.490 --> 00:48:11.400
Either you're cooking
a lot of the same thing

00:48:11.400 --> 00:48:12.210
and it gets boring.

00:48:12.210 --> 00:48:15.370
Or things tend to go bad quicker
because you're not consuming it

00:48:15.370 --> 00:48:16.200
fast enough.

00:48:16.200 --> 00:48:18.330
LEANNE BROWN: Yeah, totally.

00:48:18.330 --> 00:48:20.240
Great question actually.

00:48:20.240 --> 00:48:22.850
So, so many cookbooks are
really designed for people

00:48:22.850 --> 00:48:24.550
with families,
which is important I

00:48:24.550 --> 00:48:26.270
think because it's a big issue.

00:48:26.270 --> 00:48:28.199
And it I think it
feels more acute.

00:48:28.199 --> 00:48:30.490
It's like, oh my gosh, I have
all these people to feed.

00:48:30.490 --> 00:48:31.720
Ugh.

00:48:31.720 --> 00:48:38.270
But I really wanted for everyone
with every kind of family size

00:48:38.270 --> 00:48:40.350
with all kinds of
backgrounds to be

00:48:40.350 --> 00:48:42.540
able to recognize something
of themselves in this.

00:48:42.540 --> 00:48:45.620
And so I really tried to
make it as open as possible.

00:48:45.620 --> 00:48:50.480
And I actually thought a
lot about single people

00:48:50.480 --> 00:48:54.270
because I feel like
they're less catered to,

00:48:54.270 --> 00:48:55.650
which is very important.

00:48:55.650 --> 00:48:58.320
Because it's so difficult
when you have very little,

00:48:58.320 --> 00:49:01.860
like you cannot take advantage
of a lot of the sort of scale

00:49:01.860 --> 00:49:04.950
things that can help, if
you have a larger family.

00:49:04.950 --> 00:49:08.460
You know it can feel very
demoralizing to sometimes

00:49:08.460 --> 00:49:11.300
to cook for one or to eat the
same thing over and over again.

00:49:11.300 --> 00:49:13.050
That's one of the
reasons I have a lot of,

00:49:13.050 --> 00:49:14.930
here's how to use
up leftovers, here's

00:49:14.930 --> 00:49:17.090
how to kind of create a
few different things that

00:49:17.090 --> 00:49:20.360
have the same basic five
things over and over.

00:49:20.360 --> 00:49:22.150
I have a lot of that
kind of information

00:49:22.150 --> 00:49:23.760
because I think
that's a big deal.

00:49:23.760 --> 00:49:26.250
I have the stuff
on toast section.

00:49:26.250 --> 00:49:28.400
Is like that's what I
eat when Dan's away,

00:49:28.400 --> 00:49:31.210
or when I'm just on my own,
or when he stays late and eats

00:49:31.210 --> 00:49:32.370
at Google all the time.

00:49:40.580 --> 00:49:42.777
And I've heard from a lot
of people who are also

00:49:42.777 --> 00:49:44.360
single who said, oh
my gosh, thank you

00:49:44.360 --> 00:49:47.385
for like giving me permission
to have this be a meal.

00:49:49.970 --> 00:49:51.460
And that's actually
a big thing, is

00:49:51.460 --> 00:49:53.700
we can eat whatever we
want at any time of day.

00:49:53.700 --> 00:49:54.504
It doesn't matter.

00:49:54.504 --> 00:49:56.670
Like that's one of the
awesome things about cooking.

00:49:56.670 --> 00:49:59.340
You do not have to have a
meat with two vegetables

00:49:59.340 --> 00:50:00.390
and that's your dinner.

00:50:00.390 --> 00:50:02.340
Otherwise, you're
not doing it right.

00:50:02.340 --> 00:50:04.540
There are so many different
things that we can eat.

00:50:04.540 --> 00:50:08.570
And I think sometimes you
just need a little nudge

00:50:08.570 --> 00:50:10.560
and a reminder that
that's totally OK.

00:50:10.560 --> 00:50:12.910
And so long as you're enjoying
it that hopefully you're

00:50:12.910 --> 00:50:15.076
eating a reasonable number
of fruits and vegetables,

00:50:15.076 --> 00:50:17.740
you're fine.

00:50:17.740 --> 00:50:20.230
And sometimes that means
eating really, really simply.

00:50:20.230 --> 00:50:23.040
So I tried to design it
very much to have people

00:50:23.040 --> 00:50:26.740
from all walks of life be
able to recognize themselves.

00:50:26.740 --> 00:50:28.970
And that means to some
extent, that it's not

00:50:28.970 --> 00:50:30.650
for any one group of people.

00:50:30.650 --> 00:50:34.330
And so I'm always
shocked when people say,

00:50:34.330 --> 00:50:36.080
I've tried every single
thing in the book.

00:50:36.080 --> 00:50:37.050
I'm like, really?

00:50:37.050 --> 00:50:40.070
Because I think that people
will take it and go like,

00:50:40.070 --> 00:50:44.150
OK, there's five recipes in here
that I really like, whatever.

00:50:44.150 --> 00:50:47.856
But I can't remember where
I was going with this.

00:50:47.856 --> 00:50:49.730
GAIL SIMMONS: There's
something for everyone.

00:50:49.730 --> 00:50:51.896
LEANNE BROWN: I hope there's
something for everyone.

00:50:54.110 --> 00:50:55.760
A few weeks ago, I
had someone come up

00:50:55.760 --> 00:51:00.100
at another event I was doing and
said, you know the Roti in here

00:51:00.100 --> 00:51:02.889
is something that
we've made as a family

00:51:02.889 --> 00:51:05.430
because we're from the Caribbean
and we've made it for years.

00:51:05.430 --> 00:51:07.719
And that made us feel so
excited about this book.

00:51:07.719 --> 00:51:10.260
That this was something that we
made in our home and so maybe

00:51:10.260 --> 00:51:11.530
there were some other ideas.

00:51:11.530 --> 00:51:13.614
And I think that's just a
very natural response is

00:51:13.614 --> 00:51:15.238
if you see something,
you're like, hey,

00:51:15.238 --> 00:51:16.830
I know what that
is, I like that, it

00:51:16.830 --> 00:51:18.750
makes you trust and be
interested in the rest

00:51:18.750 --> 00:51:19.249
of the book.

00:51:19.249 --> 00:51:22.680
And so I just wanted it to
be as inviting as possible.

